commit_message:
rest: fix access to metric for owned resources

If a user owns a resource (= user_id/project_id set to its UUID) and
this resource has metrics linked to it, the user cannot access these
metrics because he's not created those metrics. Let's make sure we rely
on the metric.resource.project_id to check an access too.

Change-Id: Ibd38da9b596e4c74e477f9f7be14fb563907d7b1

commit_message:
Resource tracker: unable to restart nova compute

The resource tracker calculates its used resources. In certain cases
of failed migrations and an instance being deleted the resource tracker
causes an exception in nova compute. If this situation arises then nova
compute may not even be able to restart.

Change-Id: I4a154e0cae3b8e22bd59ed05ba708e07eed8dea7
Closes-bug: #1444439

commit_message:
Enabling multi-backend orphans existing cinder volumes.

Upon enabling multi-backend, existing cinder volumes may no longer
be usable as the "old" default cinder host name is no longer
running. You need to convert the host name of existing volumes
to the new "host@backend" type naming.

Partial-Bug: #1437761

Change-Id: I1beb83e0117bd35eb17ece8953f204f1a26089ea

commit_message:
Correct mDNS TCP/UDP socket flags

* Explicitly mark TCP and UDP as blocking sockets
* Added socket.SO_REUSEADDR to UDP socket
* Added socket.SO_REUSEPORT to TCP+UDP sockets
* Moved socket creation to inside the worker thread's
  start() method.
* Added a socket.close() to the stop() method.
* Enable eventlet patching of the "os" module, required
  to avoid symptoms which look near identical to [1].

[1]: https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/issues/210

Closes-Bug: 1444384
Change-Id: Iff642673a33d7b8d2e2c1af833f944330001c33b

commit_message:
Use lower case service in Mistral

For consistency with other projects, do not capitalize Service in
"Workflow service".

Change-Id: I069dd1d807ee1fa0e2c3df48c0545daef570cde0

commit_message:
Do not capitalize 'Service' in the service name of Magnum

Instead of 'Containers Service' (capitalized 'S'), it should be
'Containers service', like for all other projects.

Change-Id: If5fba36259f07606413956ac2adc94f3ab609bf2

When backporting commits, please make sure that they remain as similar to the commit on master or Juno. That includes the commit message.

Also, make sure that the Change-Id remains the same.

Also, please include a line with:

    
(cherry picked from commit COMMIT_ID)

Also, make sure that this commit already exists in Juno, before proposing to Icehouse.

Also, make sure that you are backporting bugs, and not features. For Icehouse, the bugs should be of High importance or Security Bug fixes.'}, {'account_id': 5112, 'date': '2015-04-09 10:18:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

i can provide now briefly.
commits on this bp https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/remove-cast-to-schedule-run-instance
plus, some more commits for API
I'll put excatly tomorrow. it's around 11pm

it seems feature but, before BP, there is a problem with rescheduling when they have resource problem ( and max retries ). so i thought it's bug.."}, {'account_id': 8213, 'date': '2015-04-09 18:40:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Well, it seems there are quite a lot of reasons not to accept this commit: It pretty much is a blueprint and even if it wouldn't be, it is a high complexity commit which changes the behaviour quite a lot, including new config options (+if a new config option is to be backported, it has to make sure that it won't change the behaviour of any existent stable deployments). You also mention some API commits? Most of such commits are not allowed to be backported to stable branches, as it might change the behaviour of existent deployments.

Please read more at: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/StableBranch#Appropriate_Fixes"}, {'account_id': 5112, 'date': '2015-04-20 10:14:26.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Networking: Setup translation for RST

Setup configuration for translation of RST. There are already
translators working on it, so let's give them uptodate strings.

Remove DocBook networking-guide.pot and create an empty file for RST.
Our proposal bot will propose updated content.

Change-Id: I10cefe311b2dd08866ab887b3962b459395e4636

That said, can you give some examples of repeating patterns you see in resources' property validation code that could be solved by schema enhancements (i.e. an enhanced schema would allow for removing those code pieces in resources)?"}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-04-17 11:27:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

[{'created': '2015-04-17 14:41:02.000000000', 'message': 'Exploit default OS credentials for clusters w/o workloads_collector user

Due to service user "workloads_collector" is not created for clusters
with older version than 6.1 after upgrade of master node, oswl
collecting procedure fails for those clusters. This fix adds workaround
to the problem by falling back to default credentials for the cluster to
be used for OS clients initialization. Please, be advised that such
approach will not work in case the user changed the credentials for the
cluster.

Change-Id: I65e9029fec3055a1e1f1179d77696b0338743663
Closes-Bug: #1444410
Closes-Bug: #1444362
'}]
commit_message:
Exploit default OS credentials for clusters w/o workloads_collector user

Due to service user "workloads_collector" is not created for clusters
with older version than 6.1 after upgrade of master node, oswl
collecting procedure fails for those clusters. This fix adds workaround
to the problem by falling back to default credentials for the cluster to
be used for OS clients initialization. Please, be advised that such
approach will not work in case the user changed the credentials for the
cluster.

Change-Id: I65e9029fec3055a1e1f1179d77696b0338743663
Closes-Bug: #1444410
Closes-Bug: #1444362

Mark some python-saharaclient jobs master only

The python34 enablement and the functional tests were only done
for master (thus liberty) but not for
kilo. Do not run the jobs on older stable releases.

[{'account_id': 15000, 'date': '2015-04-15 13:59:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-04-15 13:59:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Added more details to items per page help text

"Items per page" value setting is applicable only to those pages 
that have API supported pagination.  For example, if "Items per page"
value is set to say "3" and if we go to Admin > Identity Panel > Users
page, more than "3" items will be displayed if present.  This is
confusing to users.  So as part of this commit, the help text is modified
to reflect this limitation.

Change-Id: Ibbd4771829f0c312134eb275c797780be2b78410
Closes-Bug: 1431364

commit_message:
Get nova scheduler logs from correct place

Nova scheduler log files on CentOS are stored in different place than
on Ubuntu.
Depending what is deployment os, correct log file will be used.

Change-Id: I2e99df0ef4a7bd7e2d90aacabfe8b02b0758f3cb
Closes-Bug: #1443420

When we removed output support for git hashes we also removed parsing
support for them. This would be ok (but rough on users), except that
we also removed the test that a pure git hash is an illegal version,
which should have stayed.

Change-Id: Idd8bc470fab1711d8555a793b1294b0977ba106d
'}]
commit_message:
Reinstate pure-git-hashes-are-illegal test.

When we removed output support for git hashes we also removed parsing
support for them. This would be ok (but rough on users), except that
we also removed the test that a pure git hash is an illegal version,
which should have stayed.

Change-Id: Idd8bc470fab1711d8555a793b1294b0977ba106d

commit_message:
Implement and enable retries on Conflict

Getting Conflict errors is pretty annoying, especially when writing
automation scripts. Nova and ironic-discoverd already have their
own logic for retrying on such errors.

This patch adds 'max_retries' and 'retry_interval' arguments to
get_client for tuning or disabling retries.

Change-Id: Id9720c87ce3846faec61eb40ccf00970ca798ad2

commit_message:
Avoid restarting RabbitMQ server unnecessarily

Check that the state of the management plugin or queue mirroring
has been changed before restarting RabbitMQ server.

Change-Id: I450eaba5fe1c966f4d15da5cc826936d5bda7579
Closes-Bug: 1437978

Matthew Treinish,

Thanks for the review. I tested by applying the given patch [1], but it is not solving bug [2].

Here the problem is not with the race condition, problem with order of cleanup process.

Current code cleanup process:
1. Shutdown VM
2. Delete Snapshot
3. Delete VMs
4. Delete Volumes

Required cleanup process:
1. Delete Snapshot
2. Shutdown VM
3. Delete VMs
4. Delete Volumes

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171569/
[2] https://launchpad.net/bugs/1441554'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-04-08 14:51:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Well in that case then I definitely don't view it as a bug in tempest. If the behavior is not consistent between backends of a project that is a bug in the driver or the project. Since this is working fine in the gate as is, I view it as a bug with the gluster driver.

Think about it, as an end user of a cloud you shouldn't have to care about which backend your provider decided to use, you expect your code to use different clouds will work the same way."}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-04-08 15:07:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-04-08 15:10:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Matthew,
  I disagree, let me explain

fs-backed cinder drivers
who use hypervisor assisted snapshot feature, the only way
to delete snapshot is when Instance (server) is active, so
this testcase anyways fails for gluster cinder driver
because it is not able to delete the snap after shutting
down the instance, since hypervisor doesn't allow that
to happen

I assume that this testcase was written way back when no one
was probably using hyp assisted snaps, (LVM, ceph do not use)
so the problem never came into picture. With glusterfs (and
in near future NFS) using hyp assisted snapshots there is
no way qemu will allow deleting a snapshot of a volume
that is attached to the Instance and the Instance is in
OFF state, thus the need to delete snap first and then
turn OFF the instance in the testcase.

If we do that, it should work for all drivers, irrespective
of whether it uses hyp assisted snap or not

thanx,
deepak"}, {'account_id': 14428, 'date': '2015-04-08 15:19:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 14428, 'date': '2015-04-08 15:20:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thank you Deepak. Addressed your comment in Patch Set - 3.'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2015-04-08 15:36:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I have to agree with mtreinish... this seems like a valid scenario that Cinder and Nova (and drivers involved) need to handle, so I'm not sure why this would be considered a bug in tempest.  I think this is working around the failure in the wrong place."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-08 17:01:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

So I'm marking this as -2 because tempest is the wrong place to "fix" the issue you're hitting. Either the operation is allowed for all backend configurations of nova and cinder in which case you need to fix the gluster driver to not fail. (which I contend is the proper way to do it) Or you need to make the delete order here invalid and explicitly say so regardless of the backend configuration. Anything in between is not a position we want to be in.because it means that there is no interop between deployments with different configurations. In either case the proper place to address this is in nova and cinder first.

Iff a breaking api change is made (which it really shouldn't be, especially since that's an equal evil) to disallow this in all cases then tempest will need to be modified, but you'll have to follow the normal procedure for landing a breaking api change in that case.'}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-04-08 18:56:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14428, 'date': '2015-04-09 06:19:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi Lobankov,
Thank you very much for your time to test this patch.

Did you tested this patch when Cinder Backend is GlusteFS? Because we will face this issue only when we use GlusterFS as Cinder Backend. In that case it will call Nova to delete the snapshot. At that time VM should be in running state.

Please have a look at below logs for more details:

[1] http://logs.openstack.org/82/171482/2/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full-glusterfs-nv/2291eea/logs/screen-n-cpu.txt.gz?#_2015-04-08_20_23_58_257
[2] http://logs.openstack.org/82/171482/2/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full-glusterfs-nv/2291eea/'}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-04-09 07:12:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Matt,
    I am fine with you marking this as -2, but the issue
being fixed here is not glusterfs specific, its for any
fs-backed driver that uses hyp assisted snap (gluster being
the one currently, and in future NFS will join). Pls see
the thread @ http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-
dev/2015-April/060983.html which talks about the lack of
Nova/libvirt support to gracefully handle this in cinder
drivers that use hyp assisted snap mechanism.

  I am not tempest expert, but looking at patch
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171569/ it looks like
addcleanup_with_wait is async (can u confirm that ?)
and hence causes volume delete to happen before snap
delete, which is incorrect, since Cinder by design only
allows volume to be deleted if all snaps are deleted
beforehand (as per John's comment in the patch)

thanx,
deepak"}, {'account_id': 14428, 'date': '2015-04-20 08:16:23.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

As we are only seeing this issue in drivers which uses hypervisor assisted snapshots (currently GlusterFS), skipping these test cases for GlusterFS CI job in the patch https://review.openstack.org/173408.'}]

commit_message:
Delete snapshot before shutting down the vms

As part of "test_volume_boot_pattern" test case cleanup, current
code deletes the snapshot after shutting down the vms.

Because of this, when cinder drivers, which supports assisted
snapshots like "GlusterFS", calls nova to delete snapshots, it is
failing.

This patch modifies the tempest code to delete the snapshot, before
shutting down the vms.

Closes-Bug: 1441554
Partial-Bug: 1441050
Change-Id: Ib36537fb1b10a0f592d4de771f08e733e0edd2bb

Add db_sync to senlin-db-recreate

We don't need an additional step to recreate tables. After all, an empty
database with no tables is useless.

commit_message:
Build RequestContext in webhook middleware

Build a RequestContext based on the senlin context which is
got using context.get_service_context. This RequestContext
object will be used by webhook middleware to access DB API.

Change-Id: I49c66b22c748a96fec4b67e0be9315628500aefd

commit_message:
Sort TODO and FEATURES again

- Removed pruning of events/actions table, because it is now listed in
  FEATRUES.rst
- Removed migration to oslo.policy, because it is already done
- Removed authentication control which is completed
- Removed webhook API related items which are near completed
- Added item (Middle priority) for revising spec format.
- Moved threading model to FEATURES as low-priority, i.e. long term.
- Revised logging formatter item where the original description is not
  accurate.

Change-Id: I6ca2e73513a05a93a1964d63d619355479a95aa8

Remove routedserviceinsertion extension and replace it with
lbaasrouterinsertion extension to enable more specific
associations between LBaaS pools and routers, instead of having
an extension that allows mapping of routers to any Neutron
resources, which is unnecessary in the MidoNet plugin.

Change-Id: I1eb6ffbad8e58e4e3e2d998d9fa8831f875560dd
Implements: MNP-81
'}, {'created': '2015-04-12 07:55:20.000000000', 'message': 'lbaasrouterinsertion extension

Remove routedserviceinsertion extension and replace it with
lbaasrouterinsertion extension.  Just as was the case with
routedservcieinsertion, only implicit association between pools
and routers is supported.  routedserviceinsertion is removed
because it provided a way to map routers to any Neutron
resource, which was a feature not required for the MidoNet
plugin.  By making the association logic specific to lbaas,
unnecessary complexity was removed.

Change-Id: I1eb6ffbad8e58e4e3e2d998d9fa8831f875560dd

commit_message:
remove routedserviceinsertion extension

Remove routedserviceinsertion extension because the router and
pool associations are implicitly determined and there is no
need to maintain in DB or display to users the explicit bindings.

Change-Id: I1eb6ffbad8e58e4e3e2d998d9fa8831f875560dd
Implements: MNP-81

commit_message:
Make memcache client reusable across threads

memcache.Client is inherited from threading._local so instances are only
accessible from current thread or eventlet. Present workaround broke
inheritance  chain so super() call is unusable.

This patch makes artificial client class mimic inheritance from
threading._local while using generic object methods allowing reusability.

Change-Id: Ic5d5709695877afb995fd816bb0e4ce711b99b60
Closes-Bug: #1440493

This commit adds the dashboard scenario test to
templates/openstack_tempest_gate.sh.j2 and fixes
tempest_dashboard_login_url and tempest_dashboard_url
since horizon is always configured to use SSL.

The dashboard scenario test involves:

* checking that the home page loads without error

dashboard regressions.

Conflicts:

'}]
commit_message:
Enable dashboard scenario test

This commit adds the dashboard scenario test to
templates/openstack_tempest_gate.sh.j2 and fixes
tempest_dashboard_login_url and tempest_dashboard_url
since horizon is always configured to use SSL.

The dashboard scenario test involves:

* checking that login page is available
* ability to log in as a regular user
* checking that the home page loads without error

This is a rather simplistic set of tests but will provide valuable
feedback in the gate that we have not introduced any significant
dashboard regressions.

Conflicts:
	playbooks/roles/os_tempest/defaults/main.yml

Change-Id: I5c50e30d003080378cc660dda301150b16f45b72
Closes-Bug: #1445368
(cherry picked from commit 98bbfe81200513c82dd4d61634f67cb6f802195b)

commit_message:
Applying copy_update to all policy.json files

Adding support for dynamically updating the policy files for
nova, glance, neutron, cinder and heat. Uses the copy_update
plugin to detect any updates and applies the changes to the default
policy.json

Implements: blueprint dynamically-manage-policy.json
Change-Id: I573229d6f18a5fe32460b2373ab8b2c36ac722b4

commit_message:
Correct typo for matching non-dict ovsdb rows

As can be seen just above, the correct operator for the equality
test is '=' and not '=='. This match isn't currently being used
in the neutron code, but will be used by the OVN driver.

The previous code would also raise NotImplemented when there was
no match.

Change-Id: I17ac85d1ad68d3e207225db300f65c0df1f6e1ad

commit_message:
Create the uplink for API mode

If the cluster is not used, then we can create the fake uplink. This
patch adds the call to the script that adds the fake uplink.

Change-Id: Ibebe838d41eae0627ff26c1268c540f3fe1c0b4d
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>

commit_message:
Rework server profile using new context building

Note this is a huge patch.

1) This patch reworks the context building logic for the nova server
   and heat stack profiles. We use a precise dictionary for connection
   setup, which include senlin credential and the trust cached. We don't
   use the huge context dictionary for this purpose.
2) This patch also fixed some cases where 'domain' is missing.
3) Added new exception types that will be used whenever backend objects
   are not found.
4) Revised sample nova spec, because we now support specifying image by
   name in addition to image id.
5) Reworked SDK exception translation module so that it can handle a
   different kind of exception (from Nova). Some 'print' calls are
   removed.
6) Reworked node_create logic so that 'user' and 'project' will be
   recorded when node is created.

Change-Id: If3160a5a8cc930dcebe91172da6a8bf22d20af47

commit_message:
Use list of requests in InstancePCIRequests.obj_from_db.

InstancePCIRequests.obj_from_db assumes it's called with with a dict
of values from instances_extra table, but in some cases it's called
with just the value of pci_requests column.
This changes obj_from_db to be used with just the value of pci_requests column.

Change-Id: I7bed733c845c365081719a70b8a2f0cc9a58370c
Closes-bug: #1445040

commit_message:
Fix for L2Gateway fails if OVSDB has pre-populated
entries

The patch set fixes the problem described in the launchpad
bug 1445323 where all the OVSDB tables in MYSQL DB should
be populated correctly.

Change-Id: I753b665de93d3e924bf23cbe8fb736410cb4bc73
Closes-Bug: 1445323

commit_message:
VMware: Improve invalid container error message

This patch improves the error message when dealing with
invalid image container types. Mike had a comment in
commit 869e71c31a6e2c1753796625b060fa39848af683 to make
the error message more specific.

Change-Id: I211e570e11c8525878195e3c24ef0957e6bb526d

New feature request item: CoreOS support

We can add support to CoreOS as a special profile so that deployment and
management of docker is made easy.

commit_message:
Fix QoSSpecManageApiTest to work in parallel

Global notification list for tests in QoSSpecManageApiTest
raises mismatch exception sometimes.
Also convert stubs -> mock patch.

Change-Id: I100ac76a8ae27c92c8c3c628b119eaa61cc8d7fc
Partial-Bug: #1259463

commit_message:
Improve StackValidationFailed response in properties

In some cases, there is no information about resource and
section, where Property error raised. This patch improves
StackValidationFailed msg, so this msg look like "Property
error : resource_name.section_name.key_name: error_msg", where
section_name is section, where Property error raised, e.g.
'update_policy'.

Change-Id: Iab2a6acdec254b39983de420ab03f994cff48d89
Closes-bug: #1358512

commit_message:
VMWare: Fix spawn error due to no attribute of 'propSet'

When multiple concurrent spawns are triggered, check_instance_exists
will return those on-going spawning VMs from SDK which certain vm.propSet
are not ready populated. It could lead to VM spawn failure due to
no attribute 'propSet' error.

Closes-Bug: #1372708
Change-Id: Ie51fc87ba3a4d3f14f5b288f6dece6d7db3df4c9

commit_message:
VolMgr: reschedule only when filter_properties has retry

In the task flow for volume manager, create_volume tasks, volume gets
reschedule even when scheduler doesn't indicate so.  The problem is
the flow should not only check 'allow_reschedule' and 'request_specs',
but also (more importantly) filter_properties['retry'], which is
populated by scheduler if schedule_max_attempts is set to > 1.  This
checks was there before taskflow was introduced, but somehow the
migration missed the check for filter_properties['retry'].

This change adds back the check, so scheduler_max_attempts won't be
treated like scheduler_max_attempts = infinite.

Change-Id: Ia873617b22a2d86662ea8ea2fec5aae7f54a2058
Closes-bug: #1445561

commit_message:
Add launched_at == null () when get active instances

In some cases, terminated_at is not null but launched_at is null, we need to
query there items from db too.

Closes-Bug: 1436643
Change-Id: I9ca783aa77a18b357ba52ef51719b3ab6ff28b18

The Windows SMBFS driver inherits the Linux SMBFS driver,
overriding Windows specific methods.

This commit Ic89cffc93940b7b119cfcde3362f304c9f2875df added the
volume name as an extra argument to the _do_extend_volume in order
to check if differencing images are pointing to backing files other
than the according volume disks.

Although this is not required on Windows, this method should accept
this extra argument in order to have the same signature as the
method it overrides. At the moment, this raises the following
exception:

TypeError: _do_extend_volume() takes exactly 3 arguments (4 given)

Change-Id: I868d7de4a2c68f3fc520ba476a5660a84f440bb1
Closes-Bug: #1437290
'}]
commit_message:
Windows SMBFS: fix volume extend

The Windows SMBFS driver inherits the Linux SMBFS driver,
overriding Windows specific methods.

This commit Ic89cffc93940b7b119cfcde3362f304c9f2875df added the
volume name as an extra argument to the _do_extend_volume in order
to check if differencing images are pointing to backing files other
than the according volume disks.

Although this is not required on Windows, this method should accept
this extra argument in order to have the same signature as the
method it overrides. At the moment, this raises the following
exception:

TypeError: _do_extend_volume() takes exactly 3 arguments (4 given)

Change-Id: I868d7de4a2c68f3fc520ba476a5660a84f440bb1
Closes-Bug: #1437290

commit_message:
Fix n-cpu run with sg group in stack-screenrc

n-cpu process fail when run rejoin-stack.sh.
n-cpu process needs libvirtd group permission, however it doesn't
include in stack-screenrc.
This patch adds group permission to n-cpu run command in stack-screenrc.

Change-Id: I67b734dd19b25c0b29be64272f55f6bfeb5f6f59
Closes-Bug: #1444267

commit_message:
Append command to screenrc after we update it

If a group is specified we modify the command to run under "sg".  This
currently isn't reflected in screenrc so rejoining fails

Change-Id: I5c18ba664a6ae9ba9aaa4439a9086bc85085cd75
Closes-Bug: #1444267

The gate-python-keystoneclient-python34 job fails on
stable/icehouse with an error like

 py34 create: /home/jenkins/workspace/gate-python-keystoneclient-python34/.tox/py34
 ERROR: InterpreterNotFound: python3.4

So don't run this job on stable/icehouse.

"}]
commit_message:
Don't run -keystoneclient-python34 on stable/icehouse

The gate-python-keystoneclient-python34 job fails on
stable/icehouse with an error like

 py34 create: /home/jenkins/workspace/gate-python-keystoneclient-python34/.tox/py34
 ERROR: InterpreterNotFound: python3.4

So don't run this job on stable/icehouse.

Change-Id: I7c3a0c76f5d536870b18e2fde3e530fbe935972d

[{'created': '2015-04-16 14:19:52.000000000', 'message': "Update Get API version Curl example

Currently, `curl http://0.0.0.0:35357` and `curl http://0.0.0.0:35357/v2.0/`
no longer have the same response, since keystone has it's V3 APIs. Update
the doc to differentiate the two Curl example.

Change-Id: I08f5e3bd502ebd78ea775ea4135b5c3ffb80e9c7
"}]
commit_message:
Update Get API version Curl example

Currently, `curl http://0.0.0.0:35357` and `curl http://0.0.0.0:35357/v2.0/`
no longer have the same response, since keystone has it's V3 APIs. Update
the doc to differentiate the two Curl example.

Change-Id: I08f5e3bd502ebd78ea775ea4135b5c3ffb80e9c7

commit_message:
remove unnecessary conditionals

In several places we had else branches where a reasonable default
would do the job. This makes the code a mean cleaer and easier to
read.

Change-Id: I231e09aab85fd32b8300bc33c48d0899b728b96e

commit_message:
Role operations should not require list object permission

When using Keystone's policy.v3cloudsample.json policy file, a project admin is
supposed to be able to manage role assignments.  Unfortunately, a project admin
isn't allowed to perform these operations using python-openstackclient, as we
attempt to perform list operations for any of the object types specified (users,
groups, projects). This is done in an attempt to lookup the id of the object by
name, but we perform this list operation even when the user specifies everything
by id. This causes 403 errors.

This patch still attempts to look up the object id by name, but we catch the 403
and assume that the user specified an id if the list operation is not allowed.
This is similar to what we do with the --domain option for other commands.

Closes-bug: #1445528
Change-Id: Id95a8520e935c1092d5a22ecd8ea01f572334ac8

commit_message:
DataPort.local_port_number should not fail

This changes it to return -1 instead of KeyError. This is better because
-1 is an invalid value so the caller can check of it if it needs it but
most users can just ignore failures.

Change-Id: I790d22621ea837fa4e641b6f594e6d4f5308b903
Signed-off-by: Saggi Mizrahi <saggi.mizrahi@huawei.com>

commit_message:
Correct designate-dashboard domain detail screen

The detail screen for domains was just linking to the
update screen, which does not follow other horizon screens / UX
patterns.  This change adds a new detail screen.

Change-Id: Ice43b2d96087e607746ceaa51d13ec4810fdf3cb
Closes-Bug: #1443588

commit_message:
labs: Renames snapshot

This patch renames the last snapshot of controller and network node so as to
not cause confusion when new services are added.

Change-Id: Iecd8ffb51808028ad24af389d73522586bda76c4

commit_message:
Updates generatelabs scripts

Updates to ignore unwanted files. If someone exports their labs
scripts while having existing clusters deployed, these changes will
allow auto-ignore unwanted files while creating the compressed files.

Change-Id: I6ecae37b1d97a7c0c12854f5f3240b842da84af7

[{'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-04-09 16:20:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-09 16:34:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-training-guides-tox-slides http://logs.openstack.org/40/172140/1/check/gate-training-guides-tox-slides/96798b4/ : SUCCESS in 1m 40s'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2015-04-11 06:17:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The new text claims that all disk images are cached here. This is incorrect: the base disk images are _stored_ here, not cached, and the disk images for the cluster nodes are neither cached nor stored in this directory.

It may be a good idea to tell Windows users where to get the ISO image. However, keep in mind that the URL given by the batch scripts is always correct, whereas the URL given in this text file may or may not match whatever a user's Windows batch scripts expect. Also, the README.rst works for people wondering what the directory is good for. But if their installation fails because they have no ISO image and they wonder why, how are they going to know that the answer is in this file?

It would be better (as you suggested already) to have the Windows batch scripts download the ISO image automatically."}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-04-13 08:14:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I understand what you mean about users knowing if the answer is in this file. I would still suggest having some information here in case someone is looking there for some answers. I will update the location of the VirtualBox disk images and also update "cached" to "stored". Thanks for pointing out the obvious mistakes.'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-04-13 08:19:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-13 08:25:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Updates README for labs/img section

Refactor some stuff and add an URL for Windows users to download the
distro ISOs. It is difficult to copy the URL from the Windows command
prompt.

The log file for setup_heat_network.sh indicates that stack_status remains "CREATE_IN_PROGRESS". This could be a shortcoming of the cirros image, but it would be nice if we had some plan for dealing with this. I don't think it's a blocker for this patch, but where the script claims it's "Verifying successful creation of stack.", it isn't really. Thoughts, comments?'}, {'account_id': 9178, 'date': '2015-04-14 17:05:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I could add a loop with some sleep to check till the status becomes CREATE_COMPLETE. But in case of failure it will break the script. So I thought it's better to have that in the test scripts. Let me know what you think."}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2015-04-14 18:07:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

If the status is supposed (and able) to become CREATE_COMPLETE with our current setup, even if it takes some time, then I would wait for it. That is, wait for a reasonable amount of time and then give up and return an error. We already do that in some other scripts (you know, these "sleep 1; echo -n ." loops).'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-04-16 13:10:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
labs: Adds orchestration service to osbash

Following actions are performed by this patch:
1) Adds the heat packages to the pre-download script
2) Adds OpenStack orchestration service - heat on controller node
3) Adds verification steps for heat installation

Change-Id: Id9241b64af010c314a107330ef39f0ffcc9211b7

In general, it's a good idea to test your own code before submitting it for review. If you did, you would know two things:

a) This changeset does not work because it contains syntax errors.

b) This changeset does not work because colors in client-side scripts will only end up in log files where nobody will be able to appreciate them. The bug adressed by this patch may be somehwat misleading in this regard.

Why does this changeset edit tools/generatelabs?"}, {'account_id': 14702, 'date': '2015-04-19 11:02:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1 Workflow-1

Sorry Roger, I wasn't able to test the script. I will make sure that it doesn't happen again.
/generatelabs script was done by mistake, I made some mistake in branching."}, {'account_id': 14702, 'date': '2015-04-19 11:03:22.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Rework on it.'}]

Since not all requirements are wanted in the global-requirements, the
update.py script from requirements has a soft-update parameter to ignore
requirements that are not in global-requirements.txt.

Allow an enhanced projects.txt file that has a parameter "soft" and pass
soft-update to it.

Change-Id: I57a4b9c7471458ae7ba1c98db463e41afe7dc6b2
'}]
commit_message:
Handle "soft" repositories in requirements update

Since not all requirements are wanted in the global-requirements, the
update.py script from requirements has a soft-update parameter to ignore
requirements that are not in global-requirements.txt.

Allow an enhanced projects.txt file that has a parameter "soft" and pass
soft-update to it.

Change-Id: I57a4b9c7471458ae7ba1c98db463e41afe7dc6b2

commit_message:
Remove set_lport_up_status().

The 'up' column of a logical port is read-only from Neutron's
perspective.  It's only used as a way for OVN to communicate state
northbound.

Change-Id: I93f0d8a03b716cdfe2795014c98d3370211fbba5

From middleware layer, the service context is retrieved from the context
module shared by all cloud backends (to be extended in future). From
within senlin engine, the drivers specific to a cloud backend can use
their own service context.

This patch avoids creating a RequestContext object in webook middleware
because it only cares about certain fields.

Change-Id: I9f9b7aa8c1ee8b809d9560a78761940f554f5984
"}]
commit_message:
Abstraction layer for service context

This patch adds an abstraction layer for 'senlin' service context.
From middleware layer, the service context is retrieved from the context
module shared by all cloud backends (to be extended in future). From
within senlin engine, the drivers specific to a cloud backend can use
their own service context.

This patch avoids creating a RequestContext object in webook middleware
because it only cares about certain fields.

Change-Id: I9f9b7aa8c1ee8b809d9560a78761940f554f5984

[{'created': '2015-04-19 01:41:36.000000000', 'message': "Revisions to cluster/node db model

This patch adds 'user' and 'domain' properties to node objects so that
they can be created with needed identity information. These identity
information will later be used to authenticate with keystone when the
physical resources are to be operated, i.e. created/update/delete.

This patch also makes the 'user', 'project', 'domain' fields fit the
current data models we get from keystone. Each of these entities has an
ID field of 32 bytes, instead of 36 bytes. For nodes or clusters, the
'user' and 'project' fields cannot be NULL.

Change-Id: If7fb248d6430bc0d499d45589fd99923b200d25e
"}]
commit_message:
Revisions to cluster/node db model

This patch adds 'user' and 'domain' properties to node objects so that
they can be created with needed identity information. These identity
information will later be used to authenticate with keystone when the
physical resources are to be operated, i.e. created/update/delete.

This patch also makes the 'user', 'project', 'domain' fields fit the
current data models we get from keystone. Each of these entities has an
ID field of 32 bytes, instead of 36 bytes. For nodes or clusters, the
'user' and 'project' fields cannot be NULL.

Change-Id: If7fb248d6430bc0d499d45589fd99923b200d25e

commit_message:
Merge evacuate functional tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges evacuate functional tests.

V2 has below 2 extensions for evacuate
- os-evacuate
- os-extended-evacuate-find-host
which are merged in single plugin 'evacuate' in v2.1

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled for server tests to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: Ib3c7fd1ecc9bc9a188350a0ec42299fc01919445

[{'created': '2014-10-21 06:23:47.000000000', 'message': 'Add --os-cloud support (WIP)

This adds a new option --os-cloud that allows the configurations values
for multiple clouds to be stored in a local file and selected with
a single option.

It requires the current master of os-client-config from
http://git.openstack.org/cgit/stackforge/os-client-config

The config file is ~/.config/openstack/clouds.yaml:

Sample
------

clouds:
  fred:
    auth_url: https://x:443/
    project_name: slate
    username: fflintst
    password: pebbles
  barney:
    auth_url: https://x:443/
    project_name: cogswell
    username: rubble
    password: bambam!!

Change-Id: I4939acf8067e44ffe06a2e26fc28f1adf8985b7d

commit_message:
Add --os-cloud support

This adds a new option --os-cloud that allows the configuration values
for multiple clouds to be stored in a local file and selected with
a single option.

Internal option names have had 'os_' removed to be comptible with
the options returned from OpenStackConfig().get_one_cloud().

The config file is ~/.config/openstack/clouds.yaml:

Sample
------
clouds:
  devstack:
    auth:
      auth_url: http://192.168.122.10:35357/
      project_name: demo
      username: demo
      password: 0penstack
    region_name: RegionOne
  devstack:
     auth:
       auth_url: http://192.168.122.10:35357/
       project_name: demo
       username: demo
       password: 0penstack
     region_name: RegionOne

Co-Authored-By: Monty Taylor <mordred@inaugust.com>

commit_message:
Add support for showing limits of a specific project

Looks like the option to show limits of a specific project was
missing. This resulted in always using the authenticated project.

Change-Id: I512a05df20860ffb52af34f3b64c9eb81dae8c61
Closes-Bug: 1438379

commit_message:
Enhance OVSDB Transaction timeout configuration

OVSDB Transaction currently takes the timeout parameter
from a context object that assume to have a vsctl_timeout attribute
This doesnt fit well for other users of this class (like OVN)

This fix configure the transaction timeout in a more common way

Change-Id: I51bb8d8fdc6d061d44af828818aaf62e187795fd
Closes-Bug: #1444277

Change network_id argument to list type

- changing api network_id from string to list
- modifying test cases to accomodate network_id as list
- consolidated test_clusters and test_cluster to one

Closes-Bug: #1438341

commit_message:
Broker image selection

- Adding revised alembic version with broker and broker metadata tables
- Adding Broker and BrokerMetadata classes to objects and models
- Adding crud functionalities for broker image selection
- Modifying devstack script to set default broker and image

Change-Id: I6f76d642d9ea3c201935238086c3008cfb00b2fb

commit_message:
Defer client imports

So we really weren't deferring the loading of client libs dadgummit,
do that for real where possible.  This shaves a couple of tenths off
the static import times.

Also defer as much import-time procesing as possible.  This is a little
ugly in api.auth but this also eliminates import of the auth plugins
until they are needed.

Change-Id: Ia11d4b9cf98231d37449103fc29101dc17afb009

commit_message:
Remove link to kazoo eventlet handler

This special pypi package and link is no longer
needed since kazoo itself has a in-tree supported
eventlet handler that can now be used instead.

Change-Id: I8587e22bfc13c9c5d76971cd5ff94c0cf93b6d93

commit_message:
Rename swarm-token to discovery-url

In order to be more generic across COEs and to allow users more
options for discovery mechanisms, change swarm-token was renamed
to discovery-url.

commit_message:
Delegate magnum url search to url_for method

This change removes homemade code to search magnum endpoint and uses
keystoneclient url_for method.

Closes-Bug: #1444409
Change-Id: Ida5fc20bd4ee46ec2d6846a31c3ec79e216b73f2

commit_message:
Remove side effect in get_keystoneclient

Currently get_keystoneclient uses a side effect (keystone_client
attribute) to cache keystone client instance but it's not more required
as get_keystoneclient is called at most once, thanks to parent changes.

Closes-Bug: #1444405
Change-Id: I832f4ef90fd9ec32ebf4d97675379b73620b0646

commit_message:
Add bay status check when pod create.

Now when we create pod,we didn't check the bay status
it require.It may cause some strange error.

Change-Id: Icfb1ccb317fe849f333b0b25666a27ce80d16508
Closes-bug:#1445319
Closes-bug:#1442452

commit_message:
Fix url_exception argument to ignore URL

For doc-test.conf, it needs to be an underscore in the option to ignore
a valid URL.

Fix the option so that the opensuse URL gets ignored as desired.

Change-Id: I002897360aa6c95f89a64a05687111335a77d476

commit_message:
Use choices in config.py

The oslo_config library supports the choices keyword argument. This commit
leverages the use of choices for StrOpts in Keystone's configuration.

Change-Id: Ib276e22e56eff09ac5a43fb7b93170776806fd12
Closes-Bug: 1423973

commit_message:
Stops injecting revoke_api into TestCase

Unit tests should not be using injection. The objects that are
required by a test should be explicitly constructed and used.

Change-Id: Ia9101c45da8ae6176f8c975ad63276eb231b60c1

'}, {'created': '2014-11-14 12:19:14.000000000', 'message': "Inherited role domain calls on keystoneclient v3

This patch allows the user to perform the
following API calls through the
python-keystoneclient:

Assign role to user on projects owned by a domain:
GET /OS-INHERIT/domains/{domain_id}/users/{user_id}/roles/inherited_to_projects
List user's inherited project roles on a domain:
GET /OS-INHERIT/domains/{domain_id}/users/{user_id}/roles/inherited_to_projects
Check if user has an inherited project role on domain:
HEAD /OS-INHERIT/domains/{domain_id}/users/{user_id}/roles/{role_id}/inherited_to_projects
Revoke an inherited project role from user on domain:
DELETE /OS-INHERIT/domains/{domain_id}/users/{user_id}/roles/{role_id}/inherited_to_projects 

These same operations regarding groups instead of users are also available.

Co-Authored-By: Raildo Mascena <raildo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Samuel Medeiros <samuel@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I877168e3922cdd19868d508ef9fc34d0c7e7abcb
Closes-bug: 1367866

commit_message:
Inherited role domain calls on keystoneclient v3

This patch allows the user to perform the
following API calls through the
python-keystoneclient:

Assign role to user on projects owned by a domain:
PUT /OS-INHERIT/domains/{domain_id}/users/{user_id}/roles/inherited_to_projects
List user's inherited project roles on a domain:
GET /OS-INHERIT/domains/{domain_id}/users/{user_id}/roles/inherited_to_projects
Check if user has an inherited project role on domain:
HEAD /OS-INHERIT/domains/{domain_id}/users/{user_id}/roles/{role_id}/inherited_to_projects
Revoke an inherited project role from user on domain:
DELETE /OS-INHERIT/domains/{domain_id}/users/{user_id}/roles/{role_id}/inherited_to_projects

These same operations regarding groups instead of users are also available.

Co-Authored-By: Raildo Mascena <raildo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Samuel Medeiros <samuel@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I877168e3922cdd19868d508ef9fc34d0c7e7abcb
Closes-bug: 1367866

commit_message:
Fixing the broken functional tests

Adding creator_id for Secret and Order types
Adding sub_status and sub_status_message for Order types
This is a result of these attributes being added to the API.
This change isn't aimed to support these fields, but rather just
accepts the data so that it won't bork the tests. Actual support
for using these fields should be addressed in a follow-up patch.

Fixes bug 1441848
(cherry picked from commit f0fe464dd3b01db6effa302da710f1024408dbd7)
Change-Id: I2340b7dd1dae3806418fa99bdaad73860dda5fbc

commit_message:
Work with pymongo 3.0

pymongo 3.0 renamed mongos_enum to read_pref_mode_from_name which
was causing the unit tests to fail.

Change-Id: Iaa7fd7221c2e6c865633ef342e6b83304a1de655
Closes-Bug: 1441393
(cherry picked from commit 7c3fe6acaef6fc283c383fb79f06e388df6e6926)

commit_message:
Refactor: extract and rename unique_id method

The unique_id method wasn't using any instance variables so it
was very easy to extract. The extraction is important because
it starts to limit the dependencies between unrelated objects.

Change-Id: Id4fb9a0fe5a9b176a4b479a05e0edc77fb9058d4

commit_message:
remove useless nocatalog tests of endpoint_filter

If we specify nocatalog flag when getting token, the get_v3_catalog
method would not be called at all. So, these tests don't test
endpoint_filter. We can leave only one test to test endpoint_filter
doesn't affect nocatalog. And there is a small issue in these tests,
if require_catalog=False specified, endpoint_filter and ep_filter_assoc
would not be tested anymore.

Change-Id: I60a210126f0ca33153e218590711850eadb24fae

commit_message:
Update logging to include resource tag

We added resource tagging capability to oslo.log here:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/144813/

This patch is the first step in moving Cinder logging to use
that log keyword feature for Volumes.

To use, cinder.conf needs the following log configuration:

logging_context_format_string = \
%(asctime)s.%(msecs)03d %(levelname)s %(name)s [%(request_id)s \
%(project_name)s] %(resource)s%(message)s

Change-Id: I404233b33ec93121e01be587d958a4bb9d379eb5

commit_message:
Temporarily ignore requirements on master libs

We need to disable checks of master branch requirements in libraries
so we can release updated versions of all libs that have no capped
requirements. We can restore the checks when that is done, and then
we'll look into ways to update the tools to not update caps on
library projects.

This is a continuation of I4e4ac0580b9a1a98cc5cc9ba62d6977324a15296
adding two more libraries to the set.

Change-Id: I55072b64d3d7f85b134fde035cb0ed1b36def90c

commit_message:
Move our ObjectListBase to subclass from the Oslo one

This lets us drop a lot of the stuff in our object list base class
in favor of what is provided by oslo.

Related to blueprint versioned-objects

Change-Id: I35bebfdfe906c6e3e4e0e33fdd78b7cacfa9fd2c
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dansmith@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Start the conversion to oslo.versionedobjects

This is a first commit to make a mostly trivial step towards using
oslo.versionedobjects in Magnum. It substitutes our dict compat class
for the one in the library, and officially makes the library a
requirement.

Related to blueprint versioned-objects

Change-Id: I5788224104a0182aa2f50adc0de4bb19ab07e7d9
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dansmith@redhat.com>

Setting this as WIP.

As Assaf mentioned in PS#19, the main problem right now is figuring out how to run this on the gate, and once we do that we can work on having some script initialize whatever we need for the environment (needed folders, etc).

Currently the code fails on the functional job because of process clashing: the full-stack creates a neutron-server (in addition to the one created by devstack's ./stack.sh), and agents created afterwards get associated with the devstack's server (and not the full-stack server), causing the test to ultimately fail.

(just some thoughts in the head of the developer) I need some time to see how we can fix this: is the right solution making sure our gate job is done when no devstack processes are running, or rather dive into the code and make sure the agents associate to the correct server? This will surely effect future attempts to run concurrent full-stack tests, so we must thread lightly here."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-05 14:32:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22: Verified-1

Maru, basically it looks like so: http://www.gliffy.com/go/publish/image/7701785/L.png

 - BaseFulLStackTestCase receives an environment fixture
 - an EnvironmentFixture contains multiple fixtures (all the Neutron processes that should be started)
 - Each agent fixture has 2 configuration files, which could be initialized by other processes (for example, neutron-server initializes neutron.conf, and the others use it) or it could initialize its own config file (L3 agent will create its own l3_agent.ini).
 - Additionally, the fixtures could require other resources (OVSAgentFixture and L3AgentFixture requires OVS Bridges to be created externally by the deployer before they are started).
 - Actual process creation is done in ProcessFixture (composition, not inheritence, is associating this with other fixtures like OVSAgent and L3Agent).'}, {'account_id': 6659, 'date': '2015-04-02 13:44:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 42: Code-Review+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-21 11:36:44.000000000', 'message': "HA integration tests

To better check HA, integration tests (where actual processes are used
together with one another, as opposed to functional tests which only
check functions) are needed. This sets the ground-works of such tests:

* Define different qr/qg device names, based on the last 3 letters of
  the 'host' defined for the agent. This is done because if we have
  2 l3-agent instances, each will use the same qr/qg device names
  during creation, but only one port can be created at a time.
* Since 2 l3 agents are run at the same time, one may not be aware of
  the other's namespace and will try to delete it. Now, each agent
  will only attempt to delete namespaces with 'host' at the end of the
  namespace's name.
* Created neutron-l3-test-agent executeable to be used by future
  integration tests

Change-Id: Id5a8852d38543590b90e4bbed261a7a458071a9a

"}, {'created': '2014-11-24 16:50:45.000000000', 'message': "Add HA full-stack test

To better check HA, full-stack tests (where actual processes are used
together with one another, as opposed to functional tests which only
check functions) are needed. This sets the ground-works of such tests:

* Define different qr/qg device names, based on the last 3 letters of
  the 'host' defined for the agent. This is done because if we have
  2 l3-agent instances, each will use the same qr/qg device names
  during creation, but only one port can be created at a time.
* Since 2 l3 agents are run at the same time, one may not be aware of
  the other's namespace and will try to delete it. Now, each agent
  will only attempt to delete namespaces with 'host' at the end of the
  namespace's name.
* Created neutron-l3-test-agent executeable to be used by future
  integration tests

This is part of the integration tests effort:
 - [1/3] - Add ability to run daemonized Neutron processes
 - [2/3] - Add full-stack tests framework
 * [3/3] - Test that creating HA routers work

Related-bug: #1374947
Implements: blueprint integration-tests
Change-Id: Id5a8852d38543590b90e4bbed261a7a458071a9a

check functions) are needed. This sets the ground-works of such tests:

* Define different qr/qg device names, based on the last 3 letters of
  the 'host' defined for the agent. This is done because if we have
  2 l3-agent instances, each will use the same qr/qg device names
  during creation, but only one port can be created at a time.
* Since 2 l3 agents are run at the same time, one may not be aware of
  the other's namespace and will try to delete it. Now, each agent
  will only attempt to delete namespaces with 'host' at the end of the
  namespace's name.
* Created neutron-l3-test-agent executeable to be used by future
  integration tests

This is part of the integration tests effort:
 - [1/3] - Add ability to run daemonized Neutron processes
 - [2/3] - Add full-stack tests framework
 * [3/3] - Test that creating HA routers work

Related-bug: #1374947
Implements: blueprint integration-tests
Change-Id: Id5a8852d38543590b90e4bbed261a7a458071a9a

  the other's namespace and will try to delete it. Now, each agent
  will only attempt to delete namespaces with 'host' at the end of the
  namespace's name.
* Modified tox.ini to allow running more than one test suite at a
  time. This way, we can run full-stack together with dsvm-functional

This is part of the integration tests effort:
 - [1/3] - Add ability to run daemonized Neutron processes
 - [2/3] - Add full-stack tests framework
 * [3/3] - Test that creating HA routers work

Implements: blueprint integration-tests
Related-bug: #1374947
Change-Id: Id5a8852d38543590b90e4bbed261a7a458071a9a

commit_message:
Add full-stack test

Currently, the full-stack framework has only one test which only uses
the neutron-server. This patch adds an actual test which makes sure that
once a router is created, an actual namespace is create for it. Since
this test requires 3 processes (neutron-server, l3-agent, ovs-agent),
existing full-stack code is modified to add more streamlined support for
such code.

Partially-Implements: blueprint integration-tests
Change-Id: Id5a8852d38543590b90e4bbed261a7a458071a9a

commit_message:
Use kwargs from compute v4 proxy change_instance_metadata

The args were passed to the compute manager method in the wrong order.
We noticed this in the gate with KeyError: 'uuid' in the logs because of
the LOG.debug statement in change_instance_metadata. Just use kwargs
like rpcapi would normally.

There isn't a unit test for this since the v4 proxy code goes away in
liberty, this is for getting it into stable/kilo.

Closes-Bug: #1444728

Change-Id: Ic988f48d99e626ee5773c97904e09dbf00c5414a

- designate-coverage http://logs.openstack.org/06/169106/4/check/designate-coverage/a144c86/ : SUCCESS in 2m 34s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2015-04-15 07:50:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 8099, 'date': '2015-04-15 08:47:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I just have one question - the default policy for "create_record" in designate is "admin_or_owner", which uses the context tenant id and compares it to the domains owner tenant. 

How is this data sent to the policy check, or would users have to change the policy on the horizon side to be simpler?'}, {'account_id': 6650, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:33:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Graham - Horizon carries copy of policy files around for each service, though I think it's technically possible to share policy files if services are on the same machine and use the same policy engine version / context etc.

Within horizon the user's current project is applied to the policy engine.  So if the user's token has project_id = "foo", then that is passed to the policy engine for checks. Horizon example / default files are at:
https://github.com/openstack/horizon/tree/master/openstack_dashboard/conf

You will also notice that horizon uses project_id for policy checks, and I think the default designate policy file we had used tenant (instead of project_id).  We had to slightly alter our designate horizon copy to match this change.  Example:
https://github.com/openstack/horizon/blob/master/openstack_dashboard/conf/cinder_policy.json#L3'}, {'account_id': 9500, 'date': '2015-04-16 03:10:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1941, 'date': '2015-04-16 03:29:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8099, 'date': '2015-04-16 09:02:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Correct help messages for image-update command

Currently when you are trying to update the location of an image which
is not in queued status you will get an error from the Glance API. The
help message for --location and --copy-from arguments should be updated
to inform the user that it works only for images in queued status.

Co-Authored-By: Abhishek Talwar <abhishek.talwar@tcs.com>
Co-Authored-By: Kamil Rykowski <kamil.rykowski@intel.com>

Change-Id: I82b14ffde3f301d7ffef68e984ba4ad2ae0f8b0f
Closes-Bug: #1220809

commit_message:
Trust middleware implementation

Initial version of trust middleware implementation.

One potential pitfall is that we set 'impersonation' to 'True',
which may be inappropriate in some cases.

Change-Id: I7671998f5afc9fdff1a467d99fe4ebb61893876d

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
VMware ephemeral disks are supported

This bug was to change the documentation to indicate that vmware
external disks are now supported.  Removed the line that indicated
vmware ephemeral disks are not supported.

Closes-bug: #1399653
Change-Id: I71bcc642682903d84610969b57203d36bfeb35ae

Currently marked partial. There are a few open questions that I plan to close with the help of developers. Currently known questions:

1- the structure of a policy check in policy.json is::
      <action> : <condition>
where <action> is an API or an alias for the right hand condition. Q: Are other actions conceivable?

2- some actions look like a hierarchy, e.g.::
      compute_extension:v3:os-access-ips:discoverable
I don't think I understand that fully. What does this mean?

3- while it is fairly obvious which API an action   corresponds to, it's not always so. Is there documentation about this?

4- keystone/openstack/common/policy.py says that API attributes can be expressed in this way: *user.id*. I don't see this in any of the policy files; are there examples for this? Or examples for API attributes?

I won't have time to properly follow this up in the next three weeks or so."}, {'account_id': 15002, 'date': '2015-03-23 14:29:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 15002, 'date': '2015-03-23 14:31:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Content-wise, I think you are taking an approach of "strictly accurate"  but I suspect we want to provide something slightly more useful.  All the main instruction on the rules is good, but needs more of a lead in to explain how this works, and how it is enforced.  A "Why" before a "how".


I'm a little wary of propagating the 
is_admin" check without some caveat that it is a bad idea that has spun out of control, but that is a larger conversation.  For now, I'd recommend that you explicitly isolate a paragraph that discusses "is_admin"  as a check, and we can  exorcise that demon later.'}, {'account_id': 15002, 'date': '2015-03-23 23:22:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Path set 3 is a complete rewrite. Rather than attempting to provide a complete description from the onset, I present simple then more complex examples. After that, my syntax overview. The reference to the is_admin flag is kept in the text as well, as people will see it in current versions of policy.json. If it's deprecated, I can mention it."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-26 04:13:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Problem description: I converted the file to DocBook but am still struggling with errors caused by wrong tags for headings. 

First attempt: <section> as level 1 heading, then <title> as level 2. The build process doesn't like <section>.

Next try: <title> and <subtitle>. This time, <subtitle> isn't accepted.

I found that in other documents (install guide), <title> is used throughout. But when I apply it in my document, I am told that <title> is not expected.

(1 comment)

Encouragement is always welcome, thanks Sean.

Here are again my questions about the policy language, slightly reworded:
- why is there an is_admin flag, since we have role:admin already?
- can somebody parse "target.credential.user_id" in Juno's /etc/keystone/policy.json for me, in particular the "target" part?
- Some Juno policy files such as /etc/nova/policy.json have compound targets like "compute_extension:v3:os-admin-actions:inject_network_info". While I can guess what they mean, I wonder why sometimes there is this long colon-separated string of components, and sometimes there is a single component (e.g. in /etc/glance/policy.json)

commit_message:
A short introduction to the policy.json file

None of the manuals contains a satisfactory overview of the
syntax and semantics of policy.json. This description attempts
to close the gap; it should eventually go to the configuration
guide.

The main source is ...keystone/openstack/common/policy.py.

Change-Id: I87ae3c1be0d602aa05f26c01624f1f7cb9d576e2
Partial-Bug: #1311067

commit_message:
[install-guide] use oslo_messaging_rabbit for Cinder configuration

This solves the following issues:

Option "rabbit_host" from group "DEFAULT" is deprecated. Use option
"rabbit_host" from group "oslo_messaging_rabbit".

Option "rabbit_password" from group "DEFAULT" is deprecated. Use option
"rabbit_password" from group "oslo_messaging_rabbit".

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo.

Change-Id: I814a2f3977d3cf866b26d0da415cd4fe1eb438d6

[install-guide] fix command to create subnetworks

commit_message:
Fix index for the networking guide

Fix few issues in the networking guide indices.
Include renaming two scenarios into deployment
architectures.
Normalize architecture deployment names.
Scenarios chapter will keep the numering but the
following bug will remove them once we have completed
the documentation of all of them:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-manuals/+bug/1445597

Change-Id: If4e9a62ee05082ed7fead3b21c687421990d2558
Partially-Implements: blueprint create-networking-guide

commit_message:
Add some more comments to models/frozen.py

Some people get confused and tried to add new models in models/frozen.py
To prevent this add some more information in comments in this file.

Change-Id: Iaa52ae2a826609f94e1aa81d815ae7c082bf9204

commit_message:
Fail the test if uploading source is not set

Uploading source is provided from environment settings that can be
without default values.
To prevent failures because of empty path, let's assert it.

Change-Id: I003a2c2986dc50b1ed8962af20b389a4a236be84
Related-Bug:#1445451

commit_message:
Suppress warnings user can't fix

Requests/urllib3 started issuing warnings about certificates and SSL
that our users are unable to do anything about.  This is a very blunt
way to suppress these warnings unless --verbose or --debug is
supplied on the command line.

Being more precise in the suppression requires importing the warning
classes from urllib3 and dealing with the platforms where it has
been unvendored from requests.  Maybe in the future if there are
concerns that this mutes too much otherwise.

Change-Id: I50bb10a16222de12c5b95bfe042b92e43ea8ee7c

commit_message:
Print warning on authentication error

At least print a warning on authentication error.  I have no
idea why an exception is being ignored here because if there
is no session, nothing is going to happen.  This at least will
print some useful warning:

    (.venv)terry@f350:~/python-openstackclient$ os flavor list --os-cloud pro
    WARNING: openstackclient.shell Possible error authenticating: __init__() got an unexpected keyword argument 'asdf'
    ERROR: openstack Authentication requires 'auth_url', which should be specified in 'HTTPClient'

This error was caused by having a bogus value 'asdf' in the cloud.yaml
for the cloud pro.

Change-Id: Ie08432e0464cfa86b3b3f67ca29d3b7d23d2f46f

commit_message:
Add Swarm TemplateDefinition

This change will allow deployers to select either Kubernetes
or Swarm to be the CoE used in Magnum's bays. A Swarm bay uses
a subset of the BayModel parameters used for Kubernetes.
Node discovery is provided via Docker's public discovery
endpoint, but operators and users can override this with
Bay's discovery_url argument.

Implements: bp multiple-bay-templates

Change-Id: I5278e6d477298085d07673810e5d8813d21b7730

commit_message:
Add states generating venv and use pydot2

Make it easier for others to create the states diagrams
and use a non-broken pydot fork that is actually being
maintained (pydot2).

Change-Id: Ia16c53a513159a8f15c5d7c75e22553dc1273b37

commit_message:
Use the ability to chain exceptions correctly

In the zookeeper jobboard (and persistence backends) we
are associating the cause of a new exception when raising a
exception. Using the new exception helper we can make this
work better on py2.x and py3.x so that the py3.x version
has the chain setup correctly (while the py2.x version just
uses the class 'cause' attribute instead).

Change-Id: Ieeac2f70e1834d4612556565762ffd3be3e5b5a1

commit_message:
Load definitions without requirement checking

Requirement checking was causing library version conflicts to
bubble up through TemplateDefinition loading.

commit_message:
Readability-related changes to secret store functions

This CR introduces minor changes with the aim to improve and clean the
code a little bit. So unnecessary comments were removed and some
functions renamed to reflect more context.

The need of the spec in the secret_store function in plugin.resources
was removed in favor of always getting a valid secret model.

On the other hand, there was an unnecessary check in the store_secret
function in the resources file. It was never the case (and there
shouldn't be a case) where the "spec" is null. So that check was
erased.

Change-Id: I73f59bdcc59ea213402f08862b87b48db8146ca0

commit_message:
Consider input default values in workflow execution

If the workflow input default value is defined in the spec, the input
param does not needed to be provided for workflow execution.

Partially Implements: blueprint mistral-default-input-values

commit_message:
Revert using service role for nova user

Looks like nova still needs admin role to work.  This is probably
a security bug against nova, but that's being debated.  So, in the
mean time, need to revert this back to using admin role.

Change-Id: If8b58516032f2eb5f9782189744f22abc4ab40b5
Related-Bug: #1436050

commit_message:
updated swift deps for use in stable/kilo

swift now depends on the package pyeclib which has a library dep
of liberasurecode1, liberasurecode-dev and this commit adds the
libs to the swift install as well as the repo server.

commit_message:
Prep for Kilo 11.0.0rc1 tag

This commit moves all of the stable/kilo branches for the various
OpenStack services to the head of the stable branches using the
SHA and not the branch name.

Change-Id: I3aca38e040c12e601158dc759f434849c27b88f1

commit_message:
updated swift deps for use in stable/kilo

swift now depends on the package pyeclib which has a library dep
of liberasurecode1, liberasurecode-dev and this commit adds the
libs to the swift install as well as the repo server.

Partially-Implements: blueprint master-kilofication
(cherry picked from commit dae0cf583a6a0104d7f0c96f044e11edbe6b8a85)

Change-Id: I99ad66b31bdb3a1c106a1d4b373ee7f3ba40ed8e

commit_message:
Use identity_uri_transform

Remove deprecated keys and use identity_uri via the new transform
helper method.

Also, cleanup specs for endpoint testing to make sure Common is
fully tested.

Change-Id: I5a26d8cb83193e4bf66bb952f7973838d6acba40
Implements: blueprint identity-uri

commit_message:
Add rabbitmq max_retries and retry_interval in neutron.conf.erb

Oslo.message using rabbit_max_retries and rabbit_retry_interval to
define reconnect rabbitmq server times and interval when can not
connect to rabbitmq server.

Partial-bug: #1439968

Change-Id: I8e19c3343627d4e2316f91b4fb084c5b6486dd84

commit_message:
Fix render_config_file with_section_content to handle dup sections

Since duplicate sections are allowed within openstack conf files,
need to be able to handle them in some cases.  The first case of
this is in network where the ml2 conf is including the openvswitch
conf within it and there are a couple dup sections.  This
allows the spec tests to handle those cases.

Change-Id: I8d2733a248a6a13ab87c286ff620c71955726f86
Closes-Bug: #1444696

(1 comment)

Maybe I'm misremembering, but I thought much of the goal here was to allow a driver to implement a weigher function in code that could process various info about the storage array that a generic filter wouldn't know about.  Which means that it would be supplying actual Python methods that can be called, not mathematical formulas.

If not that, then what does "driver supplied" mean here?  These are admin-supplied/configured, not provided by the driver.

This approach also makes the capabilities hoped for in the blueprint a lot weaker:

"What's more, different backends have different metrics that are actually useful for them, and only the manufacturer really knows what these are, which makes it hard or almost impossible to create a global filter for these kind of metrics."

and

"With that, scheduler is able to share some internal wisdom of each back-ends to deal with vendor specific metrics or common metrics that vendors tend to interpret differently."

are both negated by taking this approach since we can only parse values that are standard items known by Cinder.


(Don't want to confuse things here, but in my mind this feature was really something different.)'}, {'account_id': 11903, 'date': '2014-10-17 20:27:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Based on the blueprint it seemed that the filter and goodness functions were to return equations with access to standard properties for now:

"In both cases, the function has access to details of the volume, the type, and the last reported stats from the array, e.g. volume.size type.min_iops stats.capacity

To give a concrete example for our foomatic super array, it might return:
    {
        "Backend name": "Foomatic super-array 2000";
        "Filter funtion": "(stats.n_vols < 1000) AND (stats.free_space <= volume.size) AND (volume.size <= 500)";
        "Goodness function": "(stats.percent_capacity_used < 75 ? 50 + (stats.percent_capacity_used / 2) : (stats.percent_capacity_used / 2))";
        "percent_capacity_used": 25;
        "free_space": 2575;
        "n_vols": 217;
        ...
    }"

The current version would allow an admin to access the details for host stats, qos specs, volume stats and extra specs when creating the filter and goodness functions.  There could eventually be support so that drivers can pass up vendor specific stat info by using the get_volume_stats method, too.  These driver stats could then be accessed through host_stats by an admin.  That is what was meant by "driver supplied."  For now there would only be the standard stats available to an admin through the hosts_stats object.

Thank you for the feedback.  I will also change "user" to "admin" in a couple places in the spec.'}, {'account_id': 11903, 'date': '2014-10-17 20:28:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-17 20:38:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

I agree with Eric, this spec drifts away from original blueprint.  If that is intended, please at least add driver supplied function in 'Alternatives' session and compare the Pros/Cons."}, {'account_id': 6043, 'date': '2014-10-29 15:54:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Eric and Winston, I thought the idea of this blueprint (https://blueprints.launchpad.net/cinder/+spec/filtering-weighing-with-driver-supplied-functions) was to allow any driver to supply the filter and goodness function in the stats that it returns, maybe my misinterpretation of the BP.  
I helped Anthony with this along with Duncan. Anthony and I thought that supplying the two formulas in the conf file gives the admins the most flexibility.  I don't think that each driver supplying exactly one filter and goodness function would for sufficient for all the customer needs.  We would like to give the Admins the flexibility to set the functions that best suit their environments. Hopefully we can touch base in Paris regarding this spec, it quite possible that I need to be educate on its initial intend."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2014-10-29 15:57:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add driver filter for scheduler that utilizes an evaluator

This spec proposes that a new filter and weigher be added to the Cinder
scheduler that will filter drivers and weigh volume backends based on
filtering and goodness functions that are supplied by volume backends
dynamically.  An evaluator class will be used by the filter and weigher
to evaluate the supplied functions.

blueprint filtering-weighing-with-driver-supplied-functions
Change-Id: I59b607a88953a346aa35e67e785a0417a7ce8cc9

commit_message:
Fixes race condition and boosts the scheduling performance

This patch fixes a race-condition that occurs when the
scheduler tries to check for dvr serviceable ports before
it schedules a router when a subnet is associated with
a router.

Sometimes the dhcp port creation is delayed and so the
router is not scheduled to the l3-agent.

Also it boosts the scheduling performance on dvr-snat
node for scheduling a router.

This patch will provide a work around to fix this race
condition and to boost the scheduling performance
by scheduling a router on a dvr-snat when
dhcp is enabled on the provided subnet, instead of checking
all the available ports on the subnet.

Closes-Bug: #1442494

Change-Id: I089fefdd8535bdc9ed90b3230438ab0bfb6aab4f

The full-stack framework overrides the database connection string before
every test is started, but after the test it doesn't revert the string
back to what it was originally. Since after the test the database is
deleted, the string is not actually valid once the test finished, and
this conflicts with tests which are ran on the same job (specifically

commit_message:
Revert connection option post full-stack tests

The full-stack framework overrides the database connection string before
every test is started, but after the test it doesn't revert the string
back to what it was originally. Since after the test the database is
deleted, the string is not actually valid once the test finished, and
this conflicts with tests which are ran on the same job (specifically
the retargetable tests - see associated bug). The proposed patch saves
the original connection string and reverts it after the test finishes.

Change-Id: I96c01483009084cbc2b81588a1283e84e6bcb4c4
Closes-bug: #1440797

[{'created': '2015-04-02 15:41:15.000000000', 'message': "get_rand_name should return the same length string

Previously, get_rand_name(max_length, prefix) returned a randomized
suffix integer which was concatenated to the end of the given prefix.
Effectively, the suffix was any decimal number between 1 and
0x7fffffff, so multiple calls to the function could return strings with
different length. This is unexpected since running an already
randomized name into the same function shouldn't return a different
string.

In other words, if 'x = get_rand_name()' and
'y = get_rand_name(prefix=x)', it isn't guaranteed that x == y.

The suggested solution is to randomize a number between 0x10000000 and
0xffffffff and returning its hexadecimal representation (which will
always be 8 characters), then truncating if needed. Mathematically, the
possible range of result made even larger since the top range is changed
to 0xffffffff (so we don't care about negative numbers anymore).

Change-Id: I0d5a20c676f627bce2a377e3c451043150ca734c

commit_message:
create_resource should return maximum length str

Previously, get_rand_name(max_length, prefix) returned a randomized
suffix integer which was concatenated to the end of the given prefix.
Effectively, the suffix was any decimal number between 1 and
0x7fffffff, so multiple calls to the function could return strings with
different length. This is unexpected since running an already
randomized name into the same function shouldn't return a different
string.

The suggested solution is to actually fill all the space needed until
the string is 'max_length' in size. Also, a check is added to
create_resource to make sure that it only generates a new port name if
the input prefix is less than the maximum device name and if the prefix
is long enough, don't generate a random port suffix.

Change-Id: I0d5a20c676f627bce2a377e3c451043150ca734c
